AR11 - Le Meraviglie

The focus of this semester was to look at the Xyllela Fastidiosa epidemic, which for over ten years has been ravaging olive groves that are hundreds and sometimes thousands of years old, forming the landscape and guaranteeing the economic functioning of Puglia, in order to question the potential and place of architecture faced with such a catastrophe.The entire studio began by immersing itself in the context through an exercise consisting in reproducing a work by the artist and architect Ugo La Pietra, whose practice is based inter alia on a critique of the relationship between man and the city, questioning the limits of domesticity and demonstrating a certain sensitivity to the Apulian territory, its culture, its materials and its know-how. For my part, I copied the ‘Leaf Chair’, a fragment of a collection of organically shaped steel outdoor furniture.Based on our research and reflections, we worked in pairs to come up with an architectural project. ”The Meraviglie” would be a park located to the west of the town of Ostuni, which is still relatively untouched by the epidemic. The park would include a pavilion and a series of built interventions, such as benches, kiosks, roads and paths, which would lead residents, farmers and visitors through forests, gardens, ruins and healthy, diseased or recently planted olive groves. It would offer a contemplative experience, an opportunity to raise awareness of the damage caused by the disease, as well as the alternatives envisaged to deal with it.